    "Dr. Peter S. Ruckman": "(Hebrew \u2014 Keberi. \u201cmy grave\u201d) has nothing to do with Sheol or Hades. This \u201cgrave\u201d is a hole in the ground or a niche in a cave. A huge funeral procession leaves the land of Egypt and heads [v_Exo_10_10] up into Canaan (vss. 7\u20138). Unlike the days of Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]` (Exod. 10:10, 24), the children of Israel, this time, leave their flocks and children in Egypt (50:8). \u201cAtad, which is beyond Jordan\u201d (vs. 10) gives cause for dissention. Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`-mizraim (vs. 11) is also said to be \u201cbeyond Jordan,\u201d and where this expression occurs in about ten other cases [v_Jos_13_8] (Josh. 13:8, 18:7, Judg. 5:17, etc.), it always refers to something on the EAST side of Jordan. Hence, Havernick, Gerlach, Lange, Murphy, Rosenmuller, Keil, Kurtz, Clericus, Hengstenberg, and others say that Atad and Abel `[char_Abel_Gen_4]`-mizraim were east of Jordan in the plains of Moab or near Mt. Nebo. This interpretation is probably false for two reasons.\n5. Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, as Christ does at the Rapture, will come out half way to meet his people (46:29; 1 Thess. 4).\nv. 5). None of the angels. Angels are not \u201cbegotten.\u201d \u201c...And again, I will be to him a Father, and he shall be to me a Son?\u201d Notice that here the Holy Spirit takes the prophecy given to David `[char_David_Rut_4]` about his son Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` (2 Sam. 7:14) and shows that Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` was not a \u201cborn again\u201d child of God in the Old Testament any more than Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, Isaac, Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, Noah `[char_Noah_Neh_6]`, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, and Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`. The reference was to the greater son of David `[char_David_Rut_4]` (Matt. 1:12), the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` was NOT \u201cbegotten of God.\u201d There is no new birth in the Old Testament, as we have remarked on scores of occasions. \u201c This day have I begotten thee...\u201d (\nv. 5) has three interpretations.\nv. 5). None of the angels. Angels are not \u201cbegotten.\u201d \u201c...And again, I will be to him a Father, and he shall be to me a Son?\u201d Notice that here the Holy Spirit takes the prophecy given to David `[char_David_Rut_4]` about his son [v_2Sa_7_14] Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` (2 Sam. 7:14) and shows that Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` was not a \u201cborn again\u201d child of God in the Old Testament any more than Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`, Isaac, Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`, Noah `[char_Noah_Neh_6]`, David `[char_David_Rut_4]`, and Moses `[char_Moses_Exo_2]`. The reference was to the [v_Mat_1_12] greater son of David `[char_David_Rut_4]` (Matt. 1:12), the Lord Jesus `[char_Jesus_Ref]` Christ. Solomon `[char_Solomon_Ref]` was NOT \u201cbegotten of God.\u201d There is no new birth in the Old Testament, as we have remarked on scores of occasions. \u201cThis day have I begotten thee...\u201d (\nv. 5) has three interpretations.",
    "Commentary Vol. 83": "My father made me swear, saying, lo, I die, etc.] Having reason to believe he should not live long, he sent for Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]`, and took an oath of him to do as follows; this Joseph `[char_Joseph_Ref]` would have observed to Pharaoh, to show the necessity of his application to him, and the reasonableness of his request. 840 The words of dying men are always to be regarded; their dying charge is always attended to by those who have a regard to duty and honour; but much more when an oath is annexed to them, which among all nations was reckoned sacred: in the grave which I have digged for me in the land of Canaan, there shalt thou bury me; it was usual with persons in their lifetime to prepare graves or sepulchres for themselves, as appears from the instances of Shebna, Joseph of Arimathea, and others, and so Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]` provided one for himself; and when he is said to \u201cdig\u201d it, it is not to be supposed that he dug it himself, but ordered it to be dug by his servants, and very probably this was done at the time he buried Leah. Onkelos renders it, \u201cwhich I have bought\u201d, possessed or obtained by purchase; and so the word is used in [v_Hos_3_2] (<280302>Hosea 3:2) but the cave of Machpelah, in which Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s grave was, was not bought by him, but by Abraham `[char_Abraham_Exo_17]`; for to say, as some Jewish writers f1922 suggest, that he bought Esau\u2019s part in it with a mess of pottage, is without foundation; it is better to take the words in the first sense. And now, since it was Jacob `[char_Jacob_Ref]`\u2019s desire, yea, his dying charge, to be buried in the grave he had provided for himself, the mention of this to an Egyptian king could not fail of having its desired effect; since the Egyptians, as the historian f1923 says, were more careful about their graves than about their houses: now therefore let me go up, I pray thee; to the land of Canaan, which lay higher than Egypt; and bury my father; there, in the grave he has provided for himself: and I will come again: to the land of Egypt; this he would have said, lest it should be thought he only contrived this to get an opportunity of going away to Canaan with all his wealth and riches.\nVer."
